EASTERN EQUINE ENCEPHALITIS, EQUINE - USA (11): (FLORIDA, VIRGINIA)
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: 6 Sep 2009
Source: Central Florida News [edited]
<http://www.cfnews13.com/News/Local/2009/9/6/flagler_horse_tests_positive_for_eee.html>


[This was apparently a live interview, and the questions from the
television person are in parenthesis. - Mod.TG]

For the 1st time this season, eastern equine encephalitis (EEE) has
been detected in Flagler County.

Although no human cases have been reported, health workers worry that
could change if people aren't careful.

Richard Toombs, a homeowner, has felt mosquito stings that come after
summer downpours.

"Yes, a few; every now and then you get bit," Toombs said.

County health department officials are telling residents like Toombs
to beware of mosquitoes because they could be carrying EEE, which has
already been detected in sentinel chickens in the county.

EEE is a mosquito-borne disease almost always fatal in horses. One
horse has tested positive for the disease.

Although rare, humans are susceptible as well.

"Actually, Flagler County has been fairly lucky. It hasn't shown up
in chicken flocks until recently. So we've put out an alert," said
Carl Laundrie, a county spokesman.

"(Were you aware that there was EEE in the area?) No, not until you
mentioned it," Toombs said.

Standing water is an ideal breeding ground for mosquitoes. Flagler
County residents told News 13 standing water is an issue in the county.

Mosquito control is stepping up spraying. They're also asking
homeowners to get rid of standing water.

"After heavy rains, you get standing water all along Belle Terre and
stuff like that," Toombs said. "(So it's an issue?) Yeah, I'd say so.
It doesn't really drain good."

"(Does the county have any issues with standing water throughout the
county?) Well, unfortunately, yes we do. There's a lot of standing
water in areas in the county, and that's why we have the mosquitoes,
the population we have," Laundrie said.

Sentinel chickens are chickens strategically placed throughout the
county for the sole purpose of being stung to detect diseases.

Laundrie said homeowners who want to see a mosquito spraying schedule
can log on to the East Flagler Mosquito Control District's website.

[Byline: Saul Saenz]

--
